SIMPLE: weary
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Weary
<hw>Wea"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Wearier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Weariest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>weri</ets>, AS.
<ets>w<?/rig</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>w<?/rig</ets>, OHG.
<ets>wu<?/rag</ets>; of uncertain origin; cf. AS. <ets>w<?/rian</ets> to
ramble.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the strength exhausted by toil or exertion;
worn out in respect to strength, endurance, etc.; tired;
fatigued.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I care not for my spirits if my legs were not
<qex>weary</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I] am <qex>weary</qex>, thinking of your task.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Causing weariness; tiresome.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Weary</xex> way.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧There
passed a <xex>weary</xex> time.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Coleridge.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having one's patience, relish, or contentment
exhausted; tired; sick; -- with <xex>of</xex> before the cause; <as>as,
<ex>weary</ex> of marching, or of confinement; <ex>weary</ex> of
study.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Fatigued; tiresome; irksome; wearisome.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Weary
<hw>Wea"ry</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wearied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wearying</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To reduce or exhaust the physical strength or
endurance of; to tire; to fatigue; <as>as, to <ex>weary</ex> one's self
with labor or traveling</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So shall he waste his means, <qex>weary</qex> his soldiers.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make weary of anything; to exhaust the patience
of, as by continuance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I stay too long by thee; I <qex>weary</qex> thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To harass by anything irksome.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would not cease⟦br⟧
To <qex>weary</qex> him with my assiduous cries.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To weary out</b></col>, <cd>to subdue or exhaust by
fatigue.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To jade; tire; fatigue; fag. See
<er>Jade</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Weary
<hw>Wea"ry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow tired; to become
exhausted or impatient; <as>as, to <ex>weary</ex> of an
undertaking</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weasand</ent>⟦br⟧
